# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# web/ environment template — copy to `.env.local` and fill in.
#
#   cp web/.env.example web/.env.local
#
# `.env.local` is git-ignored (see web/.gitignore → `.env*.local`); this file
# is the committed reference so contributors know which variables exist.
#
# NOTE: variables prefixed with NEXT_PUBLIC_ are inlined into the client bundle
# at build time. They are therefore PUBLIC (visible to anyone using the app) and
# must never hold secrets. They live in .env.local only to keep machine-specific
# values (like a home LAN IP) out of the public repository.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# Absolute base URL of the Django API, baked into the build.
#
# - Web build (`npm run build`): usually LEAVE UNSET. The app falls back to the
#   relative path `/fininzen/api` (same origin), which is what production uses.
#
# - Mobile build (`npm run build:mobile` / `ios:sync` / `ios:run`): REQUIRED.
#   The native WebView loads over capacitor:// or file://, so the API must be an
#   absolute, cross-origin URL reachable from the device/simulator on your LAN.
#   Point it at the machine running Docker, e.g.:
#
#     NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE=http://<YOUR_LAN_IP>/fininzen/api
#
#   Find <YOUR_LAN_IP> with `ipconfig getifaddr en0` (macOS).
#   In production this is the HTTPS domain, e.g. https://example.com/fininzen/api
NEXT_PUBLIC_API_BASE=
